VALUES
(41, 10, 31, 42, 18, 11, 14, NULL, 'Humility and Exaltation Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, where the humble are exalted and the proud are abased. This connection highlights the idea that those who appear first in society may ultimately be last in God''s eyes.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 31, 44, 13, 46, 48, 'first shall be last; and the last first', 'First and Last in Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of expectations in salvation. Mark highlights that the ''first shall be last,'' while Acts illustrates how the Gentiles, often seen as last, receive the word of God after the Jews reject it.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 32, 40, 20, 17, 19, 'going up to Jerusalem', 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus going up to Jerusalem and foretelling his suffering. They highlight the same event where Jesus prepares his disciples for his impending betrayal and death.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 32, 42, 18, 31, 34, 'going up to Jerusalem', 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize the journey to Jerusalem and Jesus'' foretelling of his suffering and death. They highlight the disciples'' lack of understanding regarding these events, showcasing a shared theme of prophecy and revelation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 32, 42, 9, 51, 51, 'going up to Jerusalem', 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' determination to go to Jerusalem. In Mark, he leads the way, while in Luke, he ''stedfastly set his face'' towards the city, highlighting his resolve.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 32, 38, 3, 8, 8, 'they were amazed', 'Connection of Servanthood and Wonder', 'This connection highlights the theme of amazement in both passages. In Mark, the disciples are ''amazed'' as Jesus approaches Jerusalem, while Zechariah speaks of men who are ''wondered at'' in relation to God''s servant, the BRANCH.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 32, 40, 13, 11, 11, NULL, 'Understanding Mysteries of the Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of revelation and understanding. In Mark, Jesus prepares his disciples for future events, while in Matthew, he explains that knowledge of the kingdom''s mysteries is granted to some but not others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 32, 41, 4, 34, 34, NULL, 'Teaching and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus teaching his disciples. In both passages, Jesus takes time to explain important matters to his followers, emphasizing their role in understanding his mission.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 32, 43, 11, 8, 8, 'they were afraid', 'Disciples'' Fear and Concern', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' fear and concern for Jesus as he approaches Jerusalem, where danger awaits. Both passages emphasize the disciples'' awareness of the threats against Jesus, reflecting their apprehension about his safety.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 33, 40, 20, 17, 19, 'the Son of man shall be delivered', 'Connection of Prophecy and Betrayal', 'Both passages emphasize the impending betrayal and condemnation of the Son of man by the chief priests and scribes. They share similar wording regarding the delivery to the Gentiles, highlighting a prophetic announcement of Jesus'' suffering and death.', 'prophecy', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 33, 40, 27, 2, 2, NULL, 'Connection of Betrayal and Delivery', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal and delivery of Jesus. In Mark 10:33, Jesus predicts being delivered to the Gentiles, while Matthew 27:2 describes Him being delivered to Pontius Pilate.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 33, 41, 8, 31, 31, 'the Son of man shall be delivered', 'Connection of Suffering and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering and rejection of the Son of man by religious leaders. Mark 8:31 introduces the theme of suffering, while Mark 10:33 specifies the condemnation and delivery to Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 33, 43, 18, 28, 28, 'shall be delivered unto the chief priests', 'Connection of Jesus'' Delivery', 'Both passages emphasize the delivery of Jesus to authorities. Mark 10:33 mentions Jesus being delivered to the chief priests, while John 18:28 describes Him being led from Caiaphas to the judgment hall, indicating the fulfillment of this delivery.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 33, 44, 3, 13, 14, NULL, 'Connection of Jesus'' Delivery', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' delivery to authorities. Both passages emphasize the act of delivering Jesus up to be condemned, linking the prophecy of Mark with the fulfillment in Acts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 33, 41, 9, 31, 31, 'the Son of man shall be delivered', 'Connection of Prophecy and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the impending death of the Son of man. They highlight the betrayal and condemnation he will face, culminating in his resurrection on the third day.', 'prophecy', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 33, 42, 9, 22, 22, 'the Son of man shall be delivered', 'Connection of Suffering and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering and rejection of the Son of man by religious authorities, culminating in his death. They highlight the inevitability of his condemnation and the role of the chief priests and scribes in this process.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 34, 40, 16, 21, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Suffering and Resurrection', 'Both passages emphasize the prediction of Jesus'' suffering and resurrection. They share similar phrases about being killed and raised again on the third day.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 34, 40, 26, 67, 67, 'shall spit upon him', 'Mocking and Abuse of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the fulfillment of the prediction in Mark 10:34 regarding the mocking and physical abuse Jesus would endure. Both passages emphasize the act of spitting on Jesus, illustrating the humiliation he faced before his crucifixion.', 'prophecy', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 34, 41, 14, 65, 65, 'shall spit upon him', 'Connection of Mocking and Scourging', 'Both passages emphasize the act of spitting on Jesus and the physical abuse he endured. Mark 10:34 predicts the mockery and suffering he would face, which is vividly illustrated in Mark 14:65 during his trial.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 34, 42, 22, 63, 65, 'mock him, and shall scourge him', 'Mocking and Scourging of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus being mocked and physically abused. Both passages describe the mocking and scourging he endured before his death.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 34, 23, 50, 6, 6, 'shall mock him, and shall scourge him', 'Connection of Suffering and Mocking', 'This connection highlights the shared theme of suffering and humiliation faced by the servant. Both passages emphasize the actions of mocking and spitting, illustrating the physical and emotional torment endured.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 34, 41, 15, 17, 20, 'mock him, and shall scourge him', 'Connection of Mocking and Scourging', 'Both passages emphasize the mocking and physical abuse Jesus endured. The SOURCE verse predicts the scorn he would face, while the TARGET passage depicts the fulfillment of that mockery and violence.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 34, 42, 23, 11, 11, 'mock him', 'Mocking and Scourging of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the mocking of Jesus. In Mark, it is foretold that he will be mocked and scourged, while in Luke, Herod and his men mock him and array him in a robe.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 35, 40, 20, 20, 28, 'we would that thou shouldest do for us whatsoever we shall desire', 'Desire for Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the request of James and John for positions of honor in Jesus'' kingdom. This connection highlights their ambition and the subsequent teaching from Jesus about true greatness and servanthood.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 35, 10, 14, 4, 11, 'thou shouldest do for us whatsoever', 'Appeal for Help', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals seeking help from a leader. Both James and John approach Jesus with a request, while the woman of Tekoah appeals to King David for assistance.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 35, 11, 2, 16, 16, 'shouldest do for us whatsoever we shall desire', 'Requests for Petitions', 'Both passages emphasize a request for a petition, with James and John asking Jesus to grant their desire and the individual in 1 Kings seeking a petition from the king. This connection highlights the theme of individuals approaching authority figures to make specific requests.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 35, 41, 1, 19, 20, NULL, 'Discipleship of James and John', 'Both passages emphasize the calling of James and John as disciples. In Mark 1:19-20, they leave their father to follow Jesus, while in Mark 10:35, they express their desires to Him, indicating their ongoing relationship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 35, 41, 5, 37, 37, 'James and John, the sons of Zebedee', 'Connection of James and John', 'This connection highlights the presence of James and John in both passages. In Mark 10:35, they approach Jesus, while in Mark 5:37, they are specifically mentioned as part of his inner circle.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 36, 11, 3, 5, 15, 'What would ye that I should do for you?', 'Divine Inquiry and Request', 'Both passages emphasize a divine inquiry where God asks what the individual desires. In Mark, Jesus asks, ''What would ye that I should do for you?'' mirroring God''s question to Solomon, ''Ask what I shall give thee.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 10, 36, 43, 15, 7, 7, 'what would ye that I should do for you', 'Asking and Receiving', 'This connection highlights the theme of asking for what one desires. Both passages emphasize the importance of communication with Jesus regarding one''s needs.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
